ce:section.ce:para:
Therefore, in this study, the R-CDs based novel fluorescent and smartphone-integrated paper sensors were developed for extremely sensitive and selective sensing of trace CBZ in medicinal Lotus seed matrix (Scheme 1
                     ). First, R-CDs with charming red fluorescence were synthesized by using citric acid and urea as precursor molecules through the solvothermal method, which could effectively avoid the autofluorescence interference of the Lotus seed matrix. The constructional and optical features of R-CDs were methodically characterized through multiple tools. Inspired by the specific fluorescence quenching mechanism of CBZ on R-CDs with a maximum quenching rate of 86%, a novel fluorescent nanosensor was constructed for supremely selective and sensitive detection of CBZ, allowing an ultralow limit of detection (LOD) of 3.5 ng/mL and a broad scope of 10–250 ng/mL. Then, the reliability of the novel fluorescent nano sensor for real-world application was verified in Lotus seed samples with fascinating recoveries of 95.5–108.3%. With the purpose of achieving the on-spot rapid sensing of CBZ, a smartphone-assisted paper-based sensor was further fabricated on the test strip by a direct deposition method. The images of the test strip taken by a smartphone were transformed and separated into red, green, and blue color channel values for on-spot rapid analysis of CBZ using the installed ‘Color Grab’ smartphone application. The ratio of the R channel to the B channel showed good linearity (R
                     2 = 0.98) with the concentration of CBZ. This work is the first report of a newly, sensitive, and portable R-CDs based sensing platform for rapid on-spot detection of CBZ in the area of food safety.
